===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A discrete division of something.
## An individual [[element]] in a larger whole; a particular [[detail]], [[thought]], or [[quality]]. {{defdate|from 13th c.}}
##: ''The Congress debated the finer '''points''' of the bill.''
## A particular [[moment]] in an [[event]] or occurrence; a [[juncture]]. {{defdate|from 13th c.}}
##: ''There comes a '''point''' in a marathon when some people give up.''
##: ''At this '''point''' in the meeting, I'd like to propose a new item for the agenda.''
## {{archaic}} [[condition|Condition]], [[state]]. {{defdate|from 13th c.}}
##: ''She was not feeling in good '''point'''.''
## A topic of discussion or debate; a [[proposition]], a focus of conversation or consideration. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
##: ''I made the '''point''' that we all had an interest to protect.''
## {{obsolete}} The smallest quantity of something; a [[jot]], a [[whit]]. {{defdate|14th-17th c.}}
##* '''1590''', Edmund Spenser, ''The Faerie Queene'', I.ii:
##*: full large of limbe and euery ioint / He was, and cared not for God or man a '''point'''.
## {{obsolete}} A tiny amount of time; a [[moment]]. {{defdate|14th-17th c.}}
## A specific [[location]] or place, seen as a spatial position. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
##: ''We should meet at a pre-arranged '''point'''.''
## {{mathematics|science}} A [[zero-dimensional]] [[mathematical object]] representing a location in one or more dimensions; something considered to have position but no magnitude or direction. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
## A [[purpose]] or [[objective]]. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
##: ''Since the decision has already been made, I see little '''point''' in further discussion.''
## A [[full stop]] or other terminal punctuation mark. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
## A distinguishing [[quality]] or [[characteristic]]. {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
##: ''Logic isn't my strong '''point'''.''
## Something tiny, as a pinprick; a very small mark. {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
##: ''The stars showed as tiny '''points''' of yellow light.''
## {{context|now only in phrases}} A [[tenth]]; formerly also a [[twelfth]]. {{defdate|from 17th c.}}
##: ''Possession is nine '''points''' of the law.''
## Each of the [[mark]]s or [[stroke]]s written above [[letter]]s, especially in Semitic languages, to indicate [[vowel]]s, stress etc. {{defdate|from 17th c.}}
## {{gaming}} A unit of [[scoring]] in a [[game]] or [[competition]]. {{defdate|from 18th c.}}
##: ''The one with the most '''points''' will win the game''
## {{mathematics}} A [[decimal point]] (now especially when reading decimal fractions aloud). {{defdate|from 18th c.}}
##: ''10.5'' ("ten point five"; = ten and a half)
## {{economics}} A unit used to express differences in prices of [[stock]]s and [[share]]s. {{defdate|from 19th c.}}
## {{typography}} a unit of measure equal to 1/12 of a [[pica]], or approximately 1/72 of an [[inch]] (exactly 1/72 of an inch in the digital era). {{defdate|from 19th c.}}
## {{UK}} An electric [[power]] socket. {{defdate|from 20th c.}}
# A sharp extremity.
## The sharp [[tip]] of an [[object]]. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
##: ''Cut the skin with the '''point''' of the knife.''
## Any projecting extremity of an object. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
## An object which has a sharp or tapering tip. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
##: ''His cowboy belt was studded with '''points'''.''
## {{backgammon}} Each of the [[twelve]] [[triangular]] positions in either [[table]] of a [[backgammon]] [[board]], on which the [[stone]]s are played. {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
## A [[peninsula]] or [[promontory]]. {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
## The position at the front or vanguard of an advancing force. {{defdate|from 16th c.}}
##* '''2005''', Martin Torgoff, ''Can't Find My Way Home: America in the Great Stoned Age, 1945–2000'', Simon & Schuster, ISBN 978-0-7432-3011-6, [http://books.google.com/books?id=j16Lsej_q-YC&pg=PA189&dq=point page 189]:
##*: Willie Jones decided to become Kimani Jones, Black Panther, on the day his best friend, Otis Nicholson, stepped on a mine while walking '''point''' during a sweep in the central highlands.
## Each of the main directions on a [[compass]], usually considered to be 32 in number; a direction. {{defdate|from 16th c.}}
## [[pointedness|Pointedness]] of speech or writing; a penetrating or decisive quality of [[expression]]. {{defdate|from 17th c.}}
##* '''1897''', Henry James, ''What Maisie Knew'':
##*: There was moreover a hint of the duchess in the infinite '''point''' with which, as she felt, she exclaimed: "And this is what you call coming ''often''?"
## {{railroads|UK}} {{qualifier|in plural ("points")}} A [[railroad switch]]. {{defdate|from 19th c.}}
## {{context|usually in plural}} An area of contrasting [[colour]] on an [[animal]], especially a dog; a marking. {{defdate|from 19th c.}}
##: ''The '''point''' color of that cat was a deep, rich sable.''
## {{cricket}} A [[fielding]] [[position]] [[square]] of the [[wicket]] on the [[off side]], between [[gully]] and [[cover]]. {{defdate|from 19th c.}}

